In Week 11, the story of Trump\'92s second term turned on a single, stark pattern: the presidency reaching for the tools of emergency, money, and fear to redraw the basic terms of American life. The week did not hinge on one spectacular crisis, but on a dense run of decisions that changed who could say no, who could be heard, and who could be counted. The Democracy Clock, which had stood at 7:49 p.m. at the end of Week 10, did not move forward in visible time, but its internal minutes crept closer to midnight. That half\uc0\u8209 minute shift captured a subtle but real tightening. The walls of lawful constraint held, yet they bowed further under the weight of a governing style that treats law as weapon, emergency as routine, and truth as clay.\
