The public time thus remains 7:49 p.m., with the underlying measure moving from 468.6 to 469.1 minutes. The face of the clock looks unchanged, but the mechanism inside has advanced. It moved because the presidency used a self\uc0\u8209 declared national emergency to impose sweeping tariffs, because allies in Congress began to translate talk of a third term into a draft change to the Constitution, and because the civil service and knowledge institutions were cut and bent to serve a narrower, more loyal state. It moved because immigration law and border power were used not as neutral tools but as instruments against students, migrants, and critics. And it did not move further only because courts, some state officials, and a handful of legislators still found ways to resist, to slow, or to expose what was being done.\
\
The most visible shift in Week 11 came through what the administration called \'93Liberation Day.\'94 Trump declared a national emergency under the National Emergencies Act and used it to impose a universal 10% tariff on all imports, with higher \'93reciprocal\'94 rates on dozens of countries. He framed this as reclaiming respect and sovereignty, but the effect was to move trade and tax policy out of Congress and into the Oval Office. The executive orders on reciprocal tariffs and synthetic opioid supply chains did more than change prices. They normalized the idea that a president can, by emergency decree, reorder the global economy. Markets reacted at once. The Dow suffered its largest two\uc0\u8209 day loss since the early pandemic, and investors watched as the dollar slid and volatility spiked. Treasury Secretary Bessent defended the tariffs with a line about cheap goods not being the essence of the American dream, turning a technical policy into a moral test of loyalty to a protectionist vision.\
