The tariff regime was not neutral. Russia, despite ongoing sanctions and conflict, was exempted from the new duties, while close allies like Canada, the UK, and the European Union were hit with steep rates on cars and other goods. Canada responded with its own 25% tariffs on U.S. vehicles. The EU and UK began formal processes for retaliation, publishing long lists of American products that could be targeted. China announced a 34% tariff on U.S. imports, export restrictions on rare earths, and new investigations into American firms. The administration then released a simple formula to justify its tariff rates, but economists and observers noted that the numbers looked back\uc0\u8209 fitted to a political choice rather than grounded in careful analysis. Economic data itself became part of the performance. It was used to defend a decision already made, not to guide what should be done.\
\
Inside the United States, the tariffs rippled through real lives. Cleveland\uc0\u8209 Cliffs idled two Minnesota operations, laying off more than 600 workers as auto supply chains buckled. Small businesses like a Florida stationery company saw their costs jump overnight and responded by suing the administration, arguing that Trump had misused emergency powers to bypass the usual investigative process required for such trade actions. The Federal Reserve, facing rising prices and shaken confidence, chose not to move interest rates, with Chair Jerome Powell citing the instability of current policy. In Congress, the Senate passed a bipartisan resolution to block tariffs on Canadian imports, and senior senators introduced the Trade Review Act to reclaim some authority over tariffs. Yet the House leadership showed no sign of bringing these measures to a vote. The pattern was clear. The presidency had seized a new economic weapon; the Senate protested; the House stood aside; and the public bore the cost.\
\
Alongside this emergency economics ran a quieter but equally consequential project: the hollowing and capture of the civil service. Under the banner of Elon Musk\'92s \'93department of government efficiency,\'94 or DOGE, the administration moved to cut tens of thousands of federal jobs. HHS alone began shedding around 10,000 positions, nearly a quarter of its workforce, including scientists, analysts, and staff who handled Freedom of Information Act requests. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the National Institutes of Health, and the Food and Drug Administration lost programs on tobacco, environmental health, infertility, and mine safety. The Administration for Community Living, which serves disabled and elderly Americans, was hit hard. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. admitted that roughly 20% of the cuts were mistakes and would need to be reversed, an extraordinary confession that the purge had been both sweeping and careless. It was a purge first, a plan second.\
