These moves did not abolish universities or museums. They did something subtler. They told administrators that funding, and even institutional autonomy, now depended on aligning content and campus politics with the preferences of the executive and its allies. A Florida law barring hires from \'93countries of concern\'94 led to the firing of a Chinese language professor who had sought asylum and had no record of misconduct. The U.S. Naval Academy ended affirmative action in admissions after a Trump order, despite earlier Supreme Court language that had carved out possible exceptions for military academies. Federal grants for arts and humanities, which support museums, archives, and educational projects across the country, were cut. Together, these actions narrowed the space in which dissenting histories, critical scholarship, and inclusive education could be pursued without fear of financial reprisal. The pressure was steady, not spectacular, but it ran through the core of civic education.\
