Looking ahead from Week 11, several decisions were already in motion. The courts would have to rule on the multistate lawsuit against Trump\'92s voting order, on the legality of the emergency tariffs, and on the deportations driven by the Alien Enemies Act point system. Congress would debate, or avoid debating, the Trade Review Act and the term\uc0\u8209 limits resolution. The Senate\'92s rebuke of Canadian tariffs would test whether bipartisan concern over economic damage could translate into sustained oversight. The Pentagon\'92s inspector general would investigate Hegseth\'92s use of Signal, and the DOGE injunction on access to federal personnel data would stand or fall on further judicial review. Each of these processes carried its own risks and possibilities, but none could be assumed to break in favor of restraint.\
